---
import Layout from '../layouts/TamilLitLayout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Archaeology of Ancient Tamil Nadu" description="Material evidence from Keeladi, Adichanallur, Kodumanal, and more confirming the history of the Sangam period.">

<section class="hist-hero">
  <div class="hh-bg"></div>
  <div class="container hh-content">
    <p class="section-label">Material Evidence of the Sangam Age</p>
    <h1 class="hh-title">
      <span class="hh-ta">அகழாய்வு</span>
      <span class="hh-en">Literature & Archaeology</span>
    </h1>
    <p class="hh-intro">
      For centuries, the Sangam poems were read merely as literature. Today, systematic archaeological excavations across Tamil Nadu are proving them to be historical records. From urban settlements to international trade, the earth is yielding the material reality of ancient Tamilakam.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- SECTION 1: KEY EXCAVATION SITES -->
<section class="hist-period" id="excavations">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="period-header">
      <div class="period-num">01</div>
      <div>
        <p class="period-era-tag">Megalithic & Iron Age</p>
        <h2 class="period-title">Major Excavation Sites</h2>
        <p class="period-title-ta">முக்கிய அகழாய்வு இடங்கள்</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="period-body">
      <div class="period-main">
        <p class="period-lead">The transition into the Megalithic Iron Age (c. 1300 BCE – 500 BCE) laid the foundation for the Sangam era. Excavations reveal a sophisticated society skilled in metallurgy, agriculture, and maritime trade.</p>

        <h3 class="period-h3">Keeladi (கீழடி) — Sivagangai District</h3>
        <p>Located near Madurai, Keeladi has revolutionized our understanding of ancient Tamil urbanism. Excavations uncovered <strong>brick structures</strong>, a well-planned <strong>drainage system</strong>, and pottery inscribed with Tamil-Brahmi script. Discoveries include glass beads, carnelian, quartz, pearls, gold ornaments, and an ivory dice. Radiocarbon dating (Beta Analytic, Florida) pushes the dates back to at least <strong>200 BCE</strong>. Artifacts indicate strong trade links with the Roman Empire, corroborating accounts in the <em>Periplus of the Erythraean Sea</em> regarding the export of steel to Alexandria.</p>

        <h3 class="period-h3">Adichanallur (ஆதிச்சநல்லூர்) — Thoothukudi District</h3>
        <p>One of the earliest and most extensive urn-burial (முதுமக்கள் தாழி) sites. Excavations yielded diverse black-and-red ware pottery, iron weapons like daggers and swords, and exquisite bronze figurines of animals (tigers, elephants, deer). Traces of gold ornaments prove that the inhabitants were skilled artisans in metal and wood.</p>

        <h3 class="period-h3">Kodumanal (கொடுமணல்) — Erode District</h3>
        <p>Identified as the 'Kodumanam' mentioned in the Sangam text <em>Pathitrupathu</em>, this site was a major industrial and trade center. Archaeologists found over 300 potsherds with Tamil-Brahmi inscriptions, spindle whorls, pieces of woven cloth, weapons, and predominantly red carnelian beads. A megalithic memorial stone was also discovered near the burial mounds.</p>

        <h3 class="period-h3">Porunthal & Paiyampalli</h3>
        <p><strong>Porunthal (Dindigul):</strong> Yielded glass beads of various colors, iron swords, and uniquely, <strong>pottery filled with rice</strong>, proving advanced agricultural practices. Sickles and spearheads were also found.<br/>
        <br/>
        <strong>Paiyampalli (Vellore):</strong> Provided evidence of iron smelting and Megalithic black-and-red ware. Radiocarbon dating places its cultural horizon around <strong>1000 BCE</strong>, showing early cultivation of horse gram and green gram.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="period-sidebar">
        <div class="sidebar-card sidebar-card--highlight">
          <p class="sc-label">Megalithic Markers</p>
          <p class="sc-val"><strong>Cists (கற்திட்டைகள்):</strong> Box-like stone structures found in Kanchipuram and Madurai.</p>
          <p class="sc-val"><strong>Menhirs (நினைவுக் கற்கள்):</strong> Monolithic standing stones erected for the dead (Tirupur, Theni).</p>
          <p class="sc-val"><strong>Hero Stones (நடுகற்கள்):</strong> Erected for fallen warriors (Dindigul, Thoothukudi).</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- SECTION 2: PALEOLITHIC ERA -->
<section class="hist-period hist-period--alt" id="paleolithic">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="period-header">
      <div class="period-num">02</div>
      <div>
        <p class="period-era-tag">Pre-Historic</p>
        <h2 class="period-title">The Dawn of Human Settlement</h2>
        <p class="period-title-ta">பழங்கற்காலம் முதல் புதிய கற்காலம் வரை</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="period-body">
      <div class="period-main">
        <p class="period-lead">Long before the Sangam era, Tamil Nadu was home to some of the earliest human ancestors in the subcontinent, dating back over 1.5 million years.</p>

        <h3 class="period-h3">The Lower Paleolithic Discovery</h3>
        <p>In 1863, British geologist <strong>Robert Bruce Foote</strong> discovered Paleolithic stone tools at Pallavaram, near Chennai. This was a watershed moment in Indian archaeology. The region around the Kosasthalaiyar river, particularly <strong>Attirampakkam</strong> and Gudiyam caves, yielded tools dating back 1.5 million years, suggesting the presence of early Hominins (Homo erectus).</p>

        <h3 class="period-h3">Mesolithic & Neolithic Transitions</h3>
        <p><strong>Mesolithic (இடைக்கற்காலம்):</strong> Hunter-gatherers used microliths (tiny stone tools made of chert and quartz). Evidence is found in the "Teri" (red sand dune) sites of Thoothukudi. Geologists suggest a land bridge existed between Tamil Nadu and Sri Lanka until 5000 BCE.</p>
        <p><strong>Neolithic (புதிய கற்காலம்):</strong> Characterized by polished stone axes called 'Celts'. Humans began domesticating animals and cultivating crops (ragi, horse gram) at sites like Paiyampalli.</p>
      </div>
      
      <div class="period-sidebar">
        <div class="sidebar-card">
          <p class="sc-label">Rock Art (பாறை ஓவியங்கள்)</p>
          <p class="sc-body">Prehistoric paintings depicting hunting and daily life survive at Keezhvalai (Villupuram), Usilampatti (Madurai), and Karikkaiyur (Nilgiris).</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- SECTION 3: ANCIENT CITIES -->
<section class="hist-period" id="ancient-cities">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="period-header">
      <div class="period-num">03</div>
      <div>
        <p class="period-era-tag">Urban Centers</p>
        <h2 class="period-title">The Great Cities of Antiquity</h2>
        <p class="period-title-ta">பண்டைய நகரங்கள்</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="period-body">
      <div class="period-main">
        <p class="period-lead">The Sangam literature vividly describes bustling capitals and international port cities. Historical and archaeological records confirm these urban centers were hubs of global commerce and learning.</p>

        <h3 class="period-h3">Poompuhar (பூம்புகார்) — The Chola Port</h3>
        <p>The legendary port city of the Cholas, deeply celebrated in the epic <em>Silappadikaram</em> and the poem <em>Pattinappaalai</em>. It was a cosmopolitan hub where Greek and Roman (Yavana) merchants resided. The city imported horses by sea, gold from northern mountains, sandalwood from the Western Ghats, and coral from the eastern seas. Poompuhar featured extensive ship-building and repair docks before being largely submerged by a tsunami around 200 CE.</p>

        <h3 class="period-h3">Madurai (மதுரை) — The Pandyan Capital</h3>
        <p>The seat of the Third Sangam, hosted by the Pandyas. According to Megasthenes and Chanakya's <em>Arthashastra</em>, Madurai was a thriving metropolis. Its proximity to the port of Korkai allowed for the massive export of pearls—records even state that Pandyan pearls were sent to King Solomon of Israel. The city boasted deep moats wide enough for elephants to march through and factories minting Roman coins.</p>

        <h3 class="period-h3">Kanchi (காஞ்சி) — The Educational Hub</h3>
        <p>Kanchipuram, the Pallava capital, was renowned as an unparalleled center of learning (Kadigai). The Chinese traveler <strong>Hiuen Tsang</strong> visited Kanchi for higher studies, ranking it among the seven sacred cities of India. The poet Kalidasa called it the "best among cities," and Thirunavukkarasar praised its limitless educational pedigree. It was the birthplace of Buddhist monk Bodhidharma and later the retirement home of the epic heroine Manimekalai.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="period-sidebar">
        <div class="sidebar-card">
          <p class="sc-label">The Traditional Divisions</p>
          <ul class="sc-list">
            <li><strong>Chola Nadu:</strong> Known for rice (சோறுடைத்து).</li>
            <li><strong>Pandya Nadu:</strong> Known for pearls (முத்துடைத்து).</li>
            <li><strong>Chera Nadu:</strong> Known for elephants (வேழமுடைத்து).</li>
            <li><strong>Thondai Nadu:</strong> Known for scholars (சான்றோருடைத்து).</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

</Layout>

<style>
.hist-hero {
  position: relative; min-height: 55vh;
  display: flex; align-items: center; padding: 9rem 0 5rem; overflow: hidden;
}
.hh-bg {
  position: absolute; inset: 0;
  background:
    radial-gradient(ellipse 80% 60% at 30% 50%, rgba(92,15,15,.4), transparent 65%),
    radial-gradient(ellipse 60% 80% at 80% 80%, rgba(201,152,58,.06), transparent 60%);
}
.hh-content { position: relative; z-index: 1; }
.hh-title { display: flex; flex-direction: column; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
.hh-ta { font-family: var(--font-tamil); font-size: clamp(1.5rem,4vw,2.8rem); color: var(--gold); font-weight: 300; }
.hh-en { font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: clamp(2rem,6vw,4.5rem); font-weight: 300; color: var(--parchment); line-height: 1.1; }
.hh-intro { font-family: var(--font-body); font-size: 1.1rem; color: var(--parchment-dark); max-width: 65ch; line-height: 1.85; }

/* PERIOD SECTIONS */
.hist-period { padding: 7rem 0; border-top: 1px solid rgba(201,152,58,.08); }
.hist-period--alt { background: var(--ink-mid); }
.hist-period--dark { background: rgba(10,7,4,.8); border-top: 1px solid rgba(139,26,26,.2); border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(139,26,26,.2); }

.period-header { display: flex; align-items: flex-start; gap: 2rem; margin-bottom: 3rem; }
.period-num { font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: 4rem; font-weight: 300; color: rgba(201,152,58,.15); line-height: 1; flex-shrink: 0; }
.period-era-tag { font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: .75rem; letter-spacing: .2em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--gold); margin-bottom: .4rem; }
.period-title { font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: clamp(1.6rem,4vw,3rem); font-weight: 400; color: var(--parchment); line-height: 1.15; margin-bottom: .3rem; }
.period-title-ta { font-family: var(--font-tamil); font-size: 1.1rem; color: var(--gold); }

.period-body { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 280px; gap: 4rem; align-items: start; }
.period-main {}
.period-lead { font-family: var(--font-body); font-size: 1.15rem; color: var(--parchment-dark); line-height: 1.9; margin-bottom: 2rem; max-width: 70ch; border-left: 3px solid var(--crimson); padding-left: 1.5rem; }
.period-h3 { font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: 1.3rem; font-weight: 500; color: var(--parchment); margin: 2rem 0 .75rem; }
.period-main p { font-family: var(--font-body); font-size: 1.02rem; color: var(--parchment-dark); line-height: 1.9; margin-bottom: 1.25rem; max-width: 70ch; }
.period-main p strong { color: var(--gold-light); }

/* SIDEBAR */
.period-sidebar { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1px; position: sticky; top: 80px; }
.sidebar-card { padding: 1.5rem; background: rgba(15,10,6,.5); border: 1px solid rgba(201,152,58,.1); border-top: 2px solid rgba(201,152,58,.2); }
.sidebar-card--highlight { border-top-color: var(--gold); }
.sc-label { font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: .68rem; letter-spacing: .15em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--gold); display: block; margin-bottom: .8rem; }
.sc-val { font-family: var(--font-body); font-size: .88rem; color: var(--parchment-dark); display: block; line-height: 1.5; margin-bottom: .8rem; }
.sc-body { font-family: var(--font-body); font-size: .88rem; color: var(--parchment-dark); line-height: 1.7; }
.sc-list { padding-left: 1rem; margin: 0; color: var(--parchment-dark); font-family: var(--font-body); font-size: .88rem; line-height: 1.7; }
.sc-list li { margin-bottom: .4rem; }
.sc-list strong { color: var(--gold-light); }

@media (max-width: 900px) {
  .period-body { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  .period-sidebar { position: static; }
}
</style>
